## What I Worked On Today

Incident response is governed by NIST SP 800-61 Rev 2 (Computer Security Incident Handling Guide) and HIPAA 45 CFR §164.308(a)(6) (Security Incident Procedures). Business continuity and disaster recovery are governed by NIST SP 800-34 Rev 1 (Contingency Planning Guide) and HIPAA 45 CFR §164.308(a)(7) (Contingency Plan). The OpenMRS SSP documents IR and CP controls; today I work through the operational depth of those controls — specific playbooks, HIPAA-specific decision points, DR architecture, and the tabletop scenario design that will test the plan against operational reality.

---

## What Actually Clicked for Me

The concept that clarified incident response today is the difference between a response procedure and a response capability.

A response procedure is a documented sequence of steps: detect, contain, eradicate, recover, post-incident activity. The procedure is necessary — it establishes the expected sequence and the decision points. But a procedure sitting in a document is not a capability. A capability is the combination of the procedure, the trained people who know how to execute it, the technical tools that support the execution, and the organizational authority structures that allow rapid decisions under pressure.

The most common incident response failure mode is not a flawed procedure — it is the gap between the procedure and the capability. The IRP says "contain the affected system by revoking the compromised credentials." The procedure is correct. The capability gap: who has the AWS console access to revoke IAM credentials at 2am? The IT Administrator does. But does the IT Administrator have the authority to take that action without Health IT Manager approval? The IRP should answer this. If it does not, the incident response stalls at a decision point while someone tries to reach the Health IT Manager.

This capability gap — authority to act without approval during an active incident — is the most common gap that tabletop exercises surface. The procedure describes what should happen; the exercise reveals whether the people involved have both the technical access and the organizational authority to make it happen in real time.

