## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

The 2am unreachable-primary-contact scenario is not hypothetical. The **2020 Universal Health Services ransomware attack** — one of the largest healthcare ransomware incidents on record, affecting approximately 400 UHS facilities — occurred over a Sunday night into Monday. Staff at multiple facilities reported that the initial response was delayed because the incident occurred outside business hours and the escalation path for reaching IT security leadership was not functioning as expected.

The UHS incident ultimately resulted in an estimated $67 million in losses — including the costs of reverting to paper records across hundreds of facilities, overtime for IT staff, and lost revenue during the recovery period.

The operational lesson is exactly what the tabletop scenario tests: the incident response plan must address not just the technical response sequence but the authority and escalation structures that allow the response to begin immediately, at any hour, without waiting for the normal business-hours approval chain to become available.

For MyClinic — a small organization where the primary contacts are a small team — the after-hours escalation path is simpler than at a large health system, but it is equally important. The IRP should name, in order: IT Administrator (immediate technical response, authority to isolate without approval), ISSO (technical leadership, first escalation), Health IT Manager (operational authority, second escalation), Executive Director/AO (organizational authority, third escalation). If the IT Administrator cannot reach anyone up the chain within 30 minutes, the IT Administrator proceeds with containment and documents all actions for review when contacts become available.

Explicitly documenting this authority delegation — in the IRP, not just understood informally — is what makes the after-hours response reliable rather than dependent on individual judgment under pressure.

