## What I Am Still Thinking About

The RPO observation — 7-day maximum data loss from the weekly S3 cross-region export — deserves a more direct follow-up than a passing mention.

For a system categorized HIGH for availability and HIGH for integrity, a 7-day RPO means that a complete regional failure scenario could require reconstructing one week of clinical encounters from paper records. For a clinic seeing [N] patients per day, that is [N × 7] patient encounters that need to be re-documented before the EHR reflects current clinical state.

The post-recovery reconciliation challenge is well-documented in healthcare IT — the 2017 WannaCry NHS attack (referenced in Day 63) produced exactly this problem at affected NHS trusts, where the mismatch between paper records accumulated during the outage and the pre-outage EHR state created patient safety risks during reconciliation.

Reducing the S3 export frequency from weekly to daily would reduce the maximum RPO from 7 days to 1 day at minimal additional cost. The technical change is straightforward — a parameter change in the RDS automated backup schedule and a corresponding S3 export job adjustment. The operational benefit — reducing the post-recovery reconciliation burden from 7 days of encounters to 1 day — is significant from a patient safety and clinical operations perspective.

I want to bring this RPO reduction as a proactive improvement proposal to the Health IT Manager before the next quarterly report — not as a POA&M finding but as a security architecture enhancement that directly reduces patient safety risk in the worst-case availability scenario.

